#: src/cargo.md:1
msgid "`Cargo.toml` conventions"
msgstr "`Cargo.toml` 慣例"

#: src/cargo.md:3
msgid "Formatting conventions"
msgstr "格式化慣例"

#: src/cargo.md:5
msgid "Use the same line width and indentation as Rust code."
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:7
msgid ""
"Put a blank line between the last key-value pair in a section and the header "
"of the next section. Do not place a blank line between section headers and "
"the key-value pairs in that section, or between key-value pairs in a section."
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:11
msgid ""
"Version-sort key names within each section, with the exception of the "
"`[package]` section. Put the `[package]` section at the top of the file; put "
"the `name` and `version` keys in that order at the top of that section, "
"followed by the remaining keys other than `description` in order, followed "
"by the `description` at the end of that section."
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:17
msgid ""
"Don't use quotes around any standard key names; use bare keys. Only use "
"quoted keys for non-standard keys whose names require them, and avoid "
"introducing such key names when possible.  See the [TOML specification]"
"(https://toml.io/en/v1.0.0#keys) for details."
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:22
msgid ""
"Put a single space both before and after the `=` between a key and value. Do "
"not indent any key names; start all key names at the start of a line."
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:25
msgid ""
"Use multi-line strings (rather than newline escape sequences) for any string "
"values that include multiple lines, such as the crate description."
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:28
msgid ""
"For array values, such as a list of features, put the entire list on the "
"same line as the key, if it fits. Otherwise, use block indentation: put a "
"newline after the opening square bracket, indent each item by one "
"indentation level, put a comma after each item (including the last), and put "
"the closing square bracket at the start of a line by itself after the last "
"item."
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:36
msgid "\"another_feature\""
msgstr "\"another_feature\""

#: src/cargo.md:37
msgid "\"yet_another_feature\""
msgstr "\"yet_another_feature\""

#: src/cargo.md:38
msgid "\"some_dependency?/some_feature\""
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:42
msgid ""
"For table values, such as a crate dependency with a path, write the entire "
"table using curly braces and commas on the same line as the key if it fits. "
"If the entire table does not fit on the same line as the key, separate it "
"out into a separate section with key-value pairs:"
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:47
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[dependencies]\n"
"crate1 = { path = \"crate1\", version = \"1.2.3\" }\n"
"\n"
"[dependencies.extremely_long_crate_name_goes_here]\n"
"path = \"extremely_long_path_name_goes_right_here\"\n"
"version = \"4.5.6\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:56
msgid "Metadata conventions"
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:58
msgid ""
"The authors list, if present, should consist of strings that each contain an "
"author name followed by an email address in angle brackets: `Full Name "
"<email@address>`. It should not contain bare email addresses, or names "
"without email addresses. (The authors list may also include a mailing list "
"address without an associated name.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:64
msgid ""
"The license field must contain a valid [SPDX expression](https://spdx.org/"
"spdx-specification-21-web-version#h.jxpfx0ykyb60), using valid [SPDX license "
"names](https://spdx.org/licenses/). (As an exception, by widespread "
"convention, the license field may use `/` in place of `OR`; for example, "
"`MIT/Apache-2.0`.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:70
msgid ""
"The homepage field, if present, must consist of a single URL, including the "
"scheme (e.g. `https://example.org/`, not just `example.org`.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/cargo.md:73
msgid ""
"Within the description field, wrap text at 80 columns. Don't start the "
"description field with the name of the crate (e.g. \"cratename is a ...\"); "
"just describe the crate itself. If providing a multi-sentence description, "
"the first sentence should go on a line by itself and summarize the crate, "
"like the subject of an email or commit message; subsequent sentences can "
"then describe the crate in more detail."
msgstr ""

#: src/SUMMARY.md:7
msgid "Expressions"
msgstr "表達式"

#: src/expressions.md:3
msgid "Blocks"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:5
msgid ""
"A block expression must have a newline after the initial `{` and before the "
"terminal `}`, unless it qualifies to be written as a single line based on "
"another style rule."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:9
msgid ""
"A keyword before the block (such as `unsafe` or `async`) must be on the same "
"line as the opening brace, with a single space between the keyword and the "
"opening brace. Indent the contents of the block."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:20 src/expressions.md:29 src/expressions.md:40
#: src/expressions.md:54
msgid "// a comment in a block\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:46
msgid "If a block has an attribute, put it on its own line before the block:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:60
msgid "Avoid writing comments on the same lines as either of the braces."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:62
msgid "Write an empty block as `{}`."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:64
msgid "Write a block on a single line if:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:66
msgid ""
"it is either used in expression position (not statement position) or is an "
"unsafe block in statement position,"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:68
msgid "it contains a single-line expression and no statements, and"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:69
msgid "it contains no comments"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:71
msgid ""
"For a single-line block, put spaces after the opening brace and before the "
"closing brace."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:74 src/expressions.md:286 src/expressions.md:750
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr "範例："

#: src/expressions.md:78
msgid "// Single line\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:82
msgid ""
"// Not allowed on one line\n"
"    // Statement position.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:88
msgid "// Contains a statement\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:96
msgid "// Contains a comment\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:98 src/expressions.md:101
msgid "// A comment\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:105
msgid "// Multiple lines\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:119
msgid "Closures"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:121
msgid ""
"Don't put any extra spaces before the first `|` (unless the closure is "
"prefixed by a keyword such as `move`); put a space between the second `|` "
"and the expression of the closure. Between the `|`s, use function definition "
"syntax, but elide types where possible."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:126
msgid ""
"Use closures without the enclosing `{}`, if possible. Add the `{}` when you "
"have a return type, when there are statements, when there are comments "
"inside the closure, or when the body expression is a control-flow expression "
"that spans multiple lines. If using braces, follow the rules above for "
"blocks. Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:157
msgid "Struct literals"
msgstr "結構體定數"

#: src/expressions.md:159
msgid ""
"If a struct literal is _small_, format it on a single line, and do not use a "
"trailing comma. If not, split it across multiple lines, with each field on "
"its own block-indented line, and use a trailing comma."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:163
msgid "For each `field: value` entry, put a space after the colon only."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:165
msgid ""
"Put a space before the opening brace. In the single-line form, put spaces "
"after the opening brace and before the closing brace."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:176
msgid ""
"Functional record update syntax is treated like a field, but it must never "
"have a trailing comma. Do not put a space after `..`."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:186
msgid "Unit literals"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:188
msgid ""
"Never break between the opening and closing parentheses of the `()` unit "
"literal."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:190
msgid "Tuple literals"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:192
msgid ""
"Use a single-line form where possible. Do not put spaces between the opening "
"parenthesis and the first element, or between the last element and the "
"closing parenthesis. Separate elements with a comma followed by a space."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:196
msgid ""
"Where a single-line form is not possible, write the tuple across multiple "
"lines, with each element of the tuple on its own block-indented line, and "
"use a trailing comma."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:209
msgid "Tuple struct literals"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:211
msgid ""
"Do not put space between the identifier and the opening parenthesis. "
"Otherwise, follow the rules for tuple literals:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:223
msgid "Enum literals"
msgstr "列舉定數"

#: src/expressions.md:225
msgid ""
"Follow the formatting rules for the various struct literals. Prefer using "
"the name of the enum as a qualifying name, unless the enum is in the prelude:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:237
msgid "Array literals"
msgstr "陣列定數"

#: src/expressions.md:239
msgid ""
"Write small array literals on a single line. Do not put spaces between the "
"opening square bracket and the first element, or between the last element "
"and the closing square bracket. Separate elements with a comma followed by a "
"space."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:243
msgid ""
"If using the repeating initializer, put a space after the semicolon only."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:246
msgid ""
"Apply the same rules if using `vec!` or similar array-like macros; always "
"use square brackets with such macros. Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:257
msgid ""
"For arrays that have to be broken across lines, if using the repeating "
"initializer, break after the `;`, not before. Otherwise, follow the rules "
"below for function calls. In any case, block-indent the contents of the "
"initializer, and put line breaks after the opening square bracket and before "
"the closing square bracket:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:277
msgid "Array accesses, indexing, and slicing"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:279
msgid ""
"Don't put spaces around the square brackets. Avoid breaking lines if "
"possible. Never break a line between the target expression and the opening "
"square bracket. If the indexing expression must be broken onto a subsequent "
"line, or spans multiple lines itself, then block-indent the indexing "
"expression, and put newlines after the opening square bracket and before the "
"closing square bracket:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:300
msgid "Unary operations"
msgstr "一元運算"

#: src/expressions.md:302
msgid ""
"Do not include a space between a unary op and its operand (i.e., `!x`, not "
"`! x`). However, there must be a space after `&mut`. Avoid line-breaking "
"between a unary operator and its operand."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:306
msgid "Binary operations"
msgstr "二元運算"

#: src/expressions.md:308
msgid ""
"Do include spaces around binary ops (i.e., `x + 1`, not `x+1`) (including "
"`=` and other assignment operators such as `+=` or `*=`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:311
msgid ""
"For comparison operators, because for `T op U`, `&T op &U` is also "
"implemented: if you have `t: &T`, and `u: U`, prefer `*t op u` to `t op &u`. "
"In general, within expressions, prefer dereferencing to taking references, "
"unless necessary (e.g. to avoid an unnecessarily expensive operation)."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:316
msgid ""
"Use parentheses liberally; do not necessarily elide them due to precedence. "
"Tools should not automatically insert or remove parentheses. Do not use "
"spaces to indicate precedence."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:320
msgid ""
"If line-breaking, block-indent each subsequent line. For assignment "
"operators, break after the operator; for all other operators, put the "
"operator on the subsequent line. Put each sub-expression on its own line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:332
msgid ""
"Prefer line-breaking at an assignment operator (either `=` or `+=`, etc.) "
"rather than at other binary operators."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:335
msgid "Casts (`as`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:337
msgid ""
"Format `as` casts like a binary operator. In particular, always include "
"spaces around `as`, and if line-breaking, break before the `as` (never "
"after) and block-indent the subsequent line. Format the type on the right-"
"hand side using the rules for types."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:342
msgid ""
"However, unlike with other binary operators, if chaining a series of `as` "
"casts that require line-breaking, and line-breaking before the first `as` "
"suffices to make the remainder fit on the next line, don't break before any "
"subsequent `as`; instead, leave the series of types all on the same line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:352
msgid ""
"If the subsequent line still requires line-breaking, break and block-indent "
"before each `as` as with other binary operators."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:355
msgid "Control flow"
msgstr "控制流程"

#: src/expressions.md:357
msgid "Do not include extraneous parentheses for `if` and `while` expressions."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:364
msgid "is better than"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:371
msgid ""
"Do include extraneous parentheses if it makes an arithmetic or logic "
"expression easier to understand (`(x * 15) + (y * 20)` is fine)"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:374
msgid "Function calls"
msgstr "函式呼叫"

#: src/expressions.md:376
msgid ""
"Do not put a space between the function name, and the opening parenthesis."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:378
msgid "Do not put a space between an argument, and the comma which follows."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:380
msgid "Do put a space between an argument, and the comma which precedes it."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:382
msgid "Prefer not to break a line in the callee expression."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:384
msgid ""
"For a function call with no arguments (a nullary function call like "
"`func()`), never break within the parentheses, and never put a space between "
"the parentheses. Always write a nullary function call as a single-line call, "
"never a multi-line call."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:389
msgid "Single-line calls"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:391
msgid ""
"Do not put a space between the function name and open paren, between the "
"open paren and the first argument, or between the last argument and the "
"close paren."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:394
msgid "Do not put a comma after the last argument."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:400
msgid "Multi-line calls"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:402
msgid ""
"If the function call is not _small_, it would otherwise over-run the max "
"width, or any argument or the callee is multi-line, then format the call "
"across multiple lines. In this case, put each argument on its own block-"
"indented line, break after the opening parenthesis and before the closing "
"parenthesis, and use a trailing comma:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:415
msgid "Method calls"
msgstr "方法呼叫"

#: src/expressions.md:417
msgid "Follow the function rules for calling."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:419
msgid "Do not put any spaces around the `.`."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:425
msgid "Macro uses"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:427
msgid ""
"If a macro can be parsed like other constructs, format it like those "
"constructs. For example, a macro use `foo!(a, b, c)` can be parsed like a "
"function call (ignoring the `!`), so format it using the rules for function "
"calls."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:432
msgid ""
"The style guide defines specific formatting for particular macros in the "
"language or standard library. The style guide does not define formatting for "
"any third-party macros, even if similar to those in the language or standard "
"library."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:437
msgid "Format string macros"
msgstr "格式化字串巨集"

#: src/expressions.md:439
msgid ""
"For macros which take a format string, if all other arguments are _small_, "
"format the arguments before the format string on a single line if they fit, "
"and format the arguments after the format string on a single line if they "
"fit, with the format string on its own line. If the arguments are not small "
"or do not fit, put each on its own line as with a function. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:447
msgid "\"Hello {} and {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:453
msgid "\"x and y were not equal, see {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:458
msgid "Chains of fields and method calls"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:460
msgid ""
"A chain is a sequence of field accesses, method calls, and/or uses of the "
"try operator `?`. E.g., `a.b.c().d` or `foo?.bar().baz?`."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:463
msgid ""
"Format the chain on one line if it is \"small\" and otherwise possible to do "
"so. If formatting on multiple lines, put each field access or method call in "
"the chain on its own line, with the line-break before the `.` and after any "
"`?`. Block-indent each subsequent line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:474
msgid ""
"If the length of the last line of the first element plus its indentation is "
"less than or equal to the indentation of the second line, then combine the "
"first and second lines if they fit. Apply this rule recursively."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:496
msgid "Multi-line elements"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:498
msgid ""
"If any element in a chain is formatted across multiple lines, put that "
"element and any later elements on their own lines."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:511
msgid ""
"Note there is block indent due to the chain and the function call in the "
"above example."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:514
msgid ""
"Prefer formatting the whole chain in multi-line style and each element on "
"one line, rather than putting some elements on multiple lines and some on a "
"single line, e.g.,"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:519
msgid "// Better\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:522 src/expressions.md:527
msgid "\"//\""
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:523
msgid "// Worse\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:531
msgid "Control flow expressions"
msgstr "控制流程表達式"

#: src/expressions.md:533
msgid ""
"This section covers `for` and `loop` expressions, as well as `if` and "
"`while` expressions with their sub-expression variants. This includes those "
"with a single `let` sub-expression (i.e. `if let` and `while let`) as well "
"as \"let-chains\": those with one or more `let` sub-expressions and one or "
"more bool-type conditions (i.e.  `if a && let Some(b) = c`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:539
msgid ""
"Put the keyword, any initial clauses, and the opening brace of the block all "
"on a single line, if they fit. Apply the usual rules for [block formatting]"
"(#blocks) to the block."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:543
msgid ""
"If there is an `else` component, then put the closing brace, `else`, any "
"following clause, and the opening brace all on the same line, with a single "
"space before and after the `else` keyword:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:563
msgid ""
"If the control line needs to be broken, then prefer breaking after the `=` "
"for any `let` sub-expression in an `if` or `while` expression that does not "
"fit, and before `in` in a `for` expression; the following line should be "
"block indented. If the control line is broken for any reason, then the "
"opening brace should be on its own line and not indented. Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:593 src/expressions.md:601 src/expressions.md:610
#: src/expressions.md:622 src/expressions.md:626 src/expressions.md:630
#: src/expressions.md:642
msgid "// ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:614
msgid ""
"A let-chain control line is allowed to be formatted on a single line "
"provided it only consists of two clauses, with the first, left-hand side "
"operand being a literal or an `ident` (which can optionally be preceded by "
"any number of unary prefix operators), and the second, right-hand side "
"operand being a single-line `let` clause. Otherwise, the control line must "
"be broken and formatted according to the above rules. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:636 src/expressions.md:648
msgid "// ..\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:652
msgid ""
"Where the initial clause spans multiple lines and ends with one or more "
"closing parentheses, square brackets, or braces, and there is nothing else "
"on that line, and that line is not indented beyond the indent on the first "
"line of the control flow expression, then put the opening brace of the block "
"on the same line with a preceding space. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:663
msgid "// Opening brace on same line as initial clause.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:668
msgid "Single line `if else`"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:670
msgid ""
"Put an `if else` or `if let else` on a single line if it occurs in "
"expression context (i.e., is not a standalone statement), it contains a "
"single `else` clause, and is _small_:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:676
msgid "// Examples that must be multi-line.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:691
msgid "Match"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:693
msgid ""
"Prefer not to line-break inside the discriminant expression. Always break "
"after the opening brace and before the closing brace. Block-indent the match "
"arms once:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:699 src/expressions.md:703
msgid "// arms\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:707
msgid "Use a trailing comma for a match arm if and only if not using a block."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:709
msgid "Never start a match arm pattern with `|`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:713
msgid "// Don't do this.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:715
msgid "// Or this.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:725
msgid "Prefer:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:739
msgid ""
"Avoid splitting the left-hand side (before the `=>`) of a match arm where "
"possible. If the right-hand side of the match arm is kept on the same line, "
"never use a block (unless the block is empty)."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:743
msgid ""
"If the right-hand side consists of multiple statements, or has line "
"comments, or the start of the line does not fit on the same line as the left-"
"hand side, use a block. Do not flatten a right-hand side block containing a "
"single macro call because its expanded form could contain a trailing "
"semicolon."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:748
msgid "Block-indent the body of a block arm."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:759
msgid "// A comment.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:767
msgid "// Trailing comma on last item.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:776
msgid ""
"If the body is a single expression with no line comments and not a control "
"flow expression, start it on the same line as the left-hand side. If not, "
"then it must be in a block. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:782
msgid "// A combinable expression.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:787
msgid "// A non-combinable expression\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:800
msgid "Line-breaking"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:802
msgid ""
"If using a block form on the right-hand side of a match arm makes it "
"possible to avoid breaking on the left-hand side, do that:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:806
msgid "// Assuming the following line does not fit in the max width\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:810
msgid "// Prefer this\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:816
msgid "// To splitting the pattern.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:819
msgid "Never break after `=>` without using the block form of the body."
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:821
msgid ""
"If the left-hand side must be split and there is an `if` clause, break "
"before the `if` and block indent. In this case, always use a block body and "
"start the body on a new line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:833
msgid ""
"If required to break the pattern, put each clause of the pattern on its own "
"line with no additional indent, breaking before the `|`. If there is an `if` "
"clause, use the above form:"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:854
msgid ""
"If the pattern is multi-line, and the last line is less wide than the "
"indent, do not put the `if` clause on a new line. E.g.,"
msgstr ""

#: src/expressions.md:867
msgid ""
"If every clause in a pattern is _small_, but the whole pattern does not fit "
"on one line, then format the pattern across multiple lines with as many "
"clauses per line as possible. Again, break before a `|`:"
