#: src/index.md:221
msgid "Comments"
msgstr "註釋"

#: src/index.md:223
msgid ""
"The following guidelines for comments are recommendations only, a mechanical "
"formatter might skip formatting of comments."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:226
msgid "Prefer line comments (`//`) to block comments (`/* ... */`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:228
msgid "When using line comments, put a single space after the opening sigil."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:230
msgid ""
"When using single-line block comments, put a single space after the opening "
"sigil and before the closing sigil. For multi-line block comments, put a "
"newline after the opening sigil, and a newline before the closing sigil."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:234
msgid ""
"Prefer to put a comment on its own line. Where a comment follows code, put a "
"single space before it. Where a block comment appears inline, use "
"surrounding whitespace as if it were an identifier or keyword."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:241
msgid "// A comment on an item.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:244
msgid "// A comment after an item.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:246
msgid "/* a comment before an argument */"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:249
msgid ""
"Comments should usually be complete sentences. Start with a capital letter, "
"end with a period (`.`). An inline block comment may be treated as a note "
"without punctuation."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:253
msgid ""
"Source lines which are entirely a comment should be limited to 80 characters "
"in length (including comment sigils, but excluding indentation) or the "
"maximum width of the line (including comment sigils and indentation), "
"whichever is smaller:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:259
msgid ""
"// This comment goes up to the ................................. 80 char "
"margin.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:262
msgid ""
"// This comment is .............................................. 80 chars "
"wide.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:271
msgid ""
"// This comment is limited by the ......................... 100 char "
"margin.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:280
msgid "Doc comments"
msgstr "文件註釋"

#: src/index.md:282
msgid "Prefer line comments (`///`) to block comments (`/** ... */`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:284
msgid ""
"Prefer outer doc comments (`///` or `/** ... */`), only use inner doc "
"comments (`//!` and `/*! ... */`) to write module-level or crate-level "
"documentation."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:287
msgid "Put doc comments before attributes."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:289
msgid "Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:291
msgid ""
"Put each attribute on its own line, indented to the level of the item. In "
"the case of inner attributes (`#!`), indent it to the level of the inside of "
"the item. Prefer outer attributes, where possible."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:295
msgid "For attributes with argument lists, format like functions."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:312
msgid ""
"For attributes with an equal sign, put a single space before and after the "
"`=`, e.g., `#[foo = 42]`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:315
msgid ""
"There must only be a single `derive` attribute. Note for tool authors: if "
"combining multiple `derive` attributes into a single attribute, the ordering "
"of the derived names must generally be preserved for correctness: "
"`#[derive(Foo)] #[derive(Bar)] struct Baz;` must be formatted to "
"`#[derive(Foo, Bar)] struct Baz;`."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:321
msgid "_small_ items"
msgstr "_小型_ 項目"

#: src/index.md:323
msgid ""
"In many places in this guide we specify formatting that depends on a code "
"construct being _small_. For example, single-line vs multi-line struct "
"literals:"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:328
msgid "// Normal formatting\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:333
msgid "// \"small\" formatting\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:338
msgid ""
"We leave it to individual tools to decide on exactly what _small_ means. In "
"particular, tools are free to use different definitions in different "
"circumstances."
msgstr ""

#: src/index.md:342
msgid ""
"Some suitable heuristics are the size of the item (in characters) or the "
"complexity of an item (for example, that all components must be simple "
"names, not more complex sub-expressions). For more discussion on suitable "
"heuristics, see [this issue](https://github.com/rust-lang-nursery/fmt-rfcs/"
"issues/47)."
msgstr ""

