#: src/editions.md:1
msgid "Rust style editions"
msgstr "Rust 風格版次"

#: src/editions.md:3
msgid ""
"The default Rust style evolves over time, as Rust does. However, to avoid "
"breaking established code style, and CI jobs checking code style, changes to "
"the default Rust style only appear in _style editions_."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:7
msgid ""
"Code written in a given [Rust edition](https://doc.rust-lang.org/edition-"
"guide/) uses the corresponding Rust style edition by default. To make it "
"easier to migrate code style separately from the semantic changes between "
"Rust editions, formatting tools such as `rustfmt` allow updating the style "
"edition separately from the Rust edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:14
msgid ""
"The current version of the style guide describes the latest Rust style "
"edition. Each distinct past style will have a corresponding archived version "
"of the style guide."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:18
msgid ""
"Note that archived versions of the style guide do not document formatting "
"for newer Rust constructs that did not exist at the time that version of the "
"style guide was archived. However, each style edition will still format all "
"constructs valid in that Rust edition, with the style of newer constructs "
"coming from the first subsequent style edition providing formatting rules "
"for that construct (without any of the systematic/global changes from that "
"style edition)."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:26
msgid ""
"Not all Rust editions have corresponding changes to the Rust style. For "
"instance, Rust 2015, Rust 2018, and Rust 2021 all use the same style edition."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:29
msgid "Rust next style edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:31
msgid ""
"Never break within a nullary function call `func()` or a unit literal `()`."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:33
msgid "Rust 2024 style edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:35
msgid ""
"This style guide describes the Rust 2024 style edition. The Rust 2024 style "
"edition is currently nightly-only and may change before the release of Rust "
"2024."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:39
msgid ""
"For a full history of changes in the Rust 2024 style edition, see the git "
"history of the style guide. Notable changes in the Rust 2024 style edition "
"include:"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:43
msgid "Miscellaneous `rustfmt` bugfixes."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:44
msgid ""
"Use version-sort (sort `x8`, `x16`, `x32`, `x64`, `x128` in that order)."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:45
msgid ""
"Change \"ASCIIbetical\" sort to Unicode-aware \"non-lowercase before "
"lowercase\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:47
msgid "Rust 2015/2018/2021 style edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/editions.md:49
msgid ""
"The archived version of the style guide at <https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rust/tree/37343f4a4d4ed7ad0891cb79e8eb25acf43fb821/src/doc/style-guide/src> "
"describes the style edition corresponding to Rust 2015, Rust 2018, and Rust "
"2021."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:1
msgid "Statements"
msgstr "陳述句"

#: src/statements.md:3
msgid "Let statements"
msgstr "let 陳述句"

#: src/statements.md:5
msgid ""
"Put a space after the `:` and on both sides of the `=` (if they are "
"present). Don't put a space before the semicolon."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:17
msgid ""
"If possible, format the declaration on a single line. If not possible, then "
"try splitting after the `=`, if the declaration fits on two lines. Block-"
"indent the expression."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:26
msgid ""
"If the first line still does not fit on a single line, split after the `:`, "
"and use block indentation. If the type requires multiple lines, even after "
"line-breaking after the `:`, then place the first line on the same line as "
"the `:`, subject to the [combining rules](expressions.html#combinable-"
"expressions)."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:37
msgid "e.g,"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:52
msgid ""
"If the expression covers multiple lines, if the first line of the expression "
"fits in the remaining space, it stays on the same line as the `=`, and the "
"rest of the expression is not further indented. If the first line does not "
"fit, then put the expression on subsequent lines, block indented. If the "
"expression is a block and the type or pattern cover multiple lines, put the "
"opening brace on a new line and not indented (this provides separation for "
"the interior of the block from the type); otherwise, the opening brace "
"follows the `=`."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:103
msgid "else blocks (let-else statements)"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:105
msgid ""
"A let statement can contain an `else` component, making it a let-else "
"statement. In this case, always apply the same formatting rules to the "
"components preceding the `else` block (i.e. the `let pattern: Type = "
"initializer_expr` portion) as described [for other let statements](#let-"
"statements)."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:110
msgid ""
"Format the entire let-else statement on a single line if all the following "
"are true:"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:113
msgid "the entire statement is _short_"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:114
msgid ""
"the `else` block contains only a single-line expression and no statements"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:115
msgid "the `else` block contains no comments"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:116
msgid ""
"the let statement components preceding the `else` block can be formatted on "
"a single line"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:122
msgid "Otherwise, the let-else statement requires some line breaks."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:124
msgid ""
"If breaking a let-else statement across multiple lines, never break between "
"the `else` and the `{`, and always break before the `}`."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:127
msgid ""
"If the let statement components preceding the `else` can be formatted on a "
"single line, but the let-else does not qualify to be placed entirely on a "
"single line, put the `else {` on the same line as the initializer "
"expression, with a space between them, then break the line after the `{`. "
"Indent the closing `}` to match the `let`, and indent the contained block "
"one step further."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:140
msgid "// nope\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:145
msgid ""
"If the let statement components preceding the `else` can be formatted on a "
"single line, but the `else {` does not fit on the same line, break the line "
"before the `else`."
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:156
msgid ""
"If the initializer expression is multi-line, put the `else` keyword and "
"opening brace of the block (i.e. `else {`) on the same line as the end of "
"the initializer expression, with a space between them, if and only if all "
"the following are true:"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:161
msgid ""
"The initializer expression ends with one or more closing parentheses, square "
"brackets, and/or braces"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:163
msgid "There is nothing else on that line"
msgstr ""

#: src/statements.md:164
msgid "That line has the same indentation level as the initial `let` keyword."
msgstr ""

